EXP 1: IMPLEMENT THE FLOW CONTROL PROTOCOL “GO BACK N”

AIM - To implement and analyze the Go-Back-N (GBN) sliding window protocol using socket programming to demonstrate reliable data transmission, cumulative acknowledgment, and error recovery via window-based retransmission.

ALGORITHM - 
Sender Side
1.	Initialize: Set base = 0, next_seq_num = 0, and define window_size (N).
2.	Send Loop:
•	If next_seq_num < base + N, send the frame and increment next_seq_num.
•	If the window is full (next_seq_num == base + N), wait for an acknowledgment (ACK).
3.	Receive ACK:
•	If a valid ACK for a frame is received, set base = ACK + 1.
•	Slide the window forward to allow new frames to be sent.
4.	Timeout Handling:
•	If a timer expires before receiving an ACK for the base frame, reset next_seq_num = base.
•	Go Back: Retransmit all frames currently in the window starting from the base.
5.	Termination: Repeat until all frames are successfully acknowledged.
Receiver Side
1.	Initialize: Set expected_seq_num = 0.
2.	Receive Frame:
•	Wait for an incoming data frame.
•	If the received frame_num == expected_seq_num:
o	Accept the frame and pass it to the network layer.
o	Send a Cumulative ACK for this frame.
o	Increment expected_seq_num.
•	Else (if the frame is out of order or corrupted):
o	Discard the frame.
o	Resend the ACK for the last successfully received frame (expected_seq_num - 1).
3.	Repeat: Continue listening for the next expected frame

